ThinkFirstThenVote2



I have one caution for women and the use of chicory root.  It can cause shedding of the uterine line to increase.  In fact it was used in the old days in high doses to abort an unwanted pregnancy.   I used to eat a breakfast cereal that contained chicory,  I developed endometriosis and had a hysterectomy.   Then I had a friend who started bleeding almost 3 weeks a month.   She offered me a fiber one bar which has chicory in it.  I read the labels though because I’m allergic to soy.   She said that they were giving her gas – I asked her how many she ate a day and how long she’d been eating them.  She’d been eating them for about 7 months — and her excessive bleeding had been going on for about 4.   I had a funny feeling and so I googled the effects of chicory.  And up came all these articles about miscarriages.  I showed them to her, she stopped eating the chicory bars (which are sold in cases at Costco).   But then here’s the real kicker.  Later that week, I went a Bible study and there was a young woman there– about 24 who asked us to pray about her having a baby – they’d been trying for 2 years.   I asked her if by chance she ate Fiber One bars — and she said that she did — every day.   I told her about the chicory articles — and the next time I saw her at a retreat 7 months later she was pregnant.  She said she got pregnant the very next month after stopping.   I’ve met two other women who were having excessive bleeding and they both ate those fiber one — or other fiber bars with chicory.   So, while it may be safe for men, women take note and if you start having ultra-heavy periods, or if you’re trying to have a baby – beware.  Save yourself from the heartache of a lost baby or feeling barren when you can simply drop the chicory bars.  What’s really sad is that pregnant women may be eating them for the extra fiber.






